1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,820
Moving on to building the power module.

2
00:00:03,580 --> 00:00:13,540
But first I want to say — the power module attaches to a cooling heat sink, and there are some requirements for it.

3
00:00:14,440 --> 00:00:20,260
It all depends, of course, on what power we're building the device for, but you still need to follow them.

4
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:30,360
Pick a heat sink by the required dimensions, and look — will we have forced cooling or not.

5
00:00:30,700 --> 00:00:36,940
If not, naturally take a heat sink with maximum cooling rib area.

6
00:00:37,540 --> 00:00:39,280
And the most important parameter.

7
00:00:40,460 --> 00:00:46,520
The wall thickness where the switch is mounted.

8
00:00:47,140 --> 00:00:53,400
It determines how well thermal power will be removed from the switch.

9
00:00:53,400 --> 00:00:57,800
For example, I'll show another type of heat sink.

10
00:00:58,620 --> 00:01:14,260
You could say it's poorly made by the manufacturer — because the thickness of the part the switch attaches to (the heat-removing part) — if you attach it like this,

11
00:01:14,740 --> 00:01:18,780
it's much thinner than the walls.

12
00:01:18,780 --> 00:01:30,760
And under a serious load, this area under the switch will overheat — it can't transfer heat to the cooling ribs fast enough.

13
00:01:30,940 --> 00:01:35,140
And such a switch can fail from overheating.

14
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:43,460
Heat sinks like this should be avoided in power builds where there'll be serious loads.

15
00:01:43,860 --> 00:01:48,080
For some small transistor, it could work.

16
00:01:48,780 --> 00:01:53,900
That's the main rule for heat sinks.

17
00:01:54,100 --> 00:02:01,460
There are also heat sinks with a copper insert — that's top class — but we don't need that here.

18
00:02:04,220 --> 00:02:09,660
What do I recommend as an insulating substrate?

19
00:02:10,200 --> 00:02:22,580
The thing is, in many FETs the drain is galvanically connected to the pad that gives off heat.

20
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:35,780
So to avoid drain-to-drain breakdown between switches, a thermally conductive insulating gasket is placed under the switches.

21
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:40,080
For critical cases I recommend using mica.

22
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:48,440
It's hard to get nowadays, but you can find it at flea markets or radio markets.

23
00:02:49,140 --> 00:02:57,330
Sometimes people sell these mica plates from Soviet high-voltage mica capacitors.

24
00:02:58,660 --> 00:03:02,220
Yes, they disassemble the cap and get these stacks of plates.

25
00:03:02,220 --> 00:03:04,900
And it's very convenient to extract them.

26
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:13,680
One such plate has dimensions of 5 by 4 cm.

27
00:03:14,420 --> 00:03:23,340
If you cut it in half, it's just enough to install two switches side by side.

28
00:03:24,340 --> 00:03:36,560
If you want to spread them apart, then it cuts into 4 pieces, and such a substrate works well in this case.

29
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:44,820
If you can't find that, you can of course use these gaskets.

30
00:03:45,590 --> 00:03:55,200
They also work, but I trust mica more, so in critical cases I use it.

31
00:03:56,820 --> 00:04:12,760
When installing a mica gasket, special attention should be paid to the hole the bolt will pass through for the switch mounting.

32
00:04:12,760 --> 00:04:15,220
Done very carefully.

33
00:04:15,360 --> 00:04:35,820
First, with an awl, carefully press and make a small puncture, and then with a Phillips screwdriver of corresponding diameter slowly expand the hole to avoid cracking

34
00:04:35,820 --> 00:04:36,400
the mica.

35
00:04:38,860 --> 00:04:47,560
Now I'll install the switch here, level the substrate, and show on the example of this hole how it's done.

36
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:59,720
The gasket is installed — level it by the switch dimensions so the mica extends equally on all sides of the switch.

37
00:05:01,060 --> 00:05:04,220
Then tighten the screw, fixing it.

38
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:19,500
After this take the awl and, at the center of the hole where the bolt will pass, carefully press and slightly twist the awl.

39
00:05:27,690 --> 00:05:36,750
Carefully — first a white dot appears at this spot.

40
00:05:49,560 --> 00:05:56,200
With such rotating motions carefully make the first chip.

41
00:06:00,150 --> 00:06:04,690
After this the awl easily passes into the hole.

42
00:06:05,130 --> 00:06:11,430
And then with the Phillips screwdriver bring the hole to the needed diameter.

43
00:06:11,430 --> 00:06:13,750
Again very carefully,

44
00:06:17,620 --> 00:06:27,980
after which you can pass through the hole with the bolt thread.

45
00:06:44,730 --> 00:06:47,590
Do this carefully too.

46
00:06:53,020 --> 00:07:05,780
Then you need to drive the bolt several times back and forth, and we'll have hole dimensions exactly fitting the screw.

47
00:07:08,060 --> 00:07:14,640
That's all the subtleties with the mica gasket.

48
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:21,940
After the holes were made, you need to remove everything unnecessary from the heat sink surface.

49
00:07:22,340 --> 00:07:28,800
These will be tiny mica pieces, because mica is rock.

50
00:07:29,080 --> 00:07:35,680
And if it gets under the gasket, there'll be a bump, and the thermal contact will worsen.

51
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:52,480
For this take a napkin, clean the gasket surface, then flip it over, clean the heat sink surface, clean from inside.

52
00:07:57,960 --> 00:08:03,360
We do the same with the second gasket.

53
00:08:12,730 --> 00:08:19,530
And further wipe the heat sink surface.

54
00:08:22,490 --> 00:08:26,230
Now we can move to applying thermal paste.

55
00:08:27,230 --> 00:08:30,190
KPT-8 thermal paste.

56
00:08:46,390 --> 00:08:49,090
The tube is new — lots of liquid.

57
00:08:50,270 --> 00:08:52,250
The liquid should be removed.

58
00:09:00,280 --> 00:09:03,680
And here's the thermal paste itself.

59
00:09:21,750 --> 00:09:29,230
Evenly distribute a layer of thermal paste over the surface.

60
00:09:31,630 --> 00:09:36,370
The back of the transistor can help with this.

61
00:09:40,140 --> 00:09:41,880
We move on to the rest.

62
00:09:42,880 --> 00:09:44,260
In

63
00:10:00,310 --> 00:10:02,270
general, the principle is clear.

64
00:10:03,490 --> 00:10:05,450
Even smoothing.

65
00:10:06,890 --> 00:10:15,070
And after this you can install the gasket in its place.

66
00:10:35,100 --> 00:10:39,460
The same operation with the second.

67
00:10:40,440 --> 00:10:50,540
After the second is installed, wipe excess thermal paste off the heat sink surface.

68
00:10:55,320 --> 00:11:01,180
And we can move to mounting the power switches.

69
00:11:06,830 --> 00:11:17,330
Now, per the rules of part placement in the box, we need to mark which side the transistors connected to plus will be on.

70
00:11:19,070 --> 00:11:22,030
The relay is on this side.

71
00:11:22,470 --> 00:11:27,250
Per the schematic, it'll be connected to plus power.

72
00:11:27,690 --> 00:11:30,510
The battery will be located like this.

73
00:11:30,510 --> 00:11:36,590
Which means the transistors connected to plus will be on this side.

74
00:11:38,150 --> 00:11:39,150
Mark.

75
00:11:40,770 --> 00:11:43,190
Moving to mounting the switches.

76
00:11:44,810 --> 00:11:49,370
Apply thermal paste to the power switches too.

77
00:12:06,700 --> 00:12:09,880
With smoothing motions like this.

78
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:16,880
Distribute the thermal paste across the entire heat sink area.

79
00:12:34,850 --> 00:12:42,530
Screws for fastening the switches should have wide heads.

80
00:12:43,570 --> 00:12:51,730
And if there aren't any, screw on a nut and put on a washer so the clamping action is good.

81
00:12:51,730 --> 00:12:56,550
And long enough too, since aluminum is thin metal.

82
00:12:57,150 --> 00:13:03,770
The screw body should go well into the aluminum wall thickness.

83
00:13:27,510 --> 00:13:30,110
Don't tighten too hard.

84
00:13:32,270 --> 00:13:40,770
We'll still need to align the switches to the holes on the plastic cover.

85
00:13:58,830 --> 00:14:02,210
So they rotate easily.

86
00:14:03,250 --> 00:14:14,650
Before installing the second pair, we need to take care of the contact terminal for connecting the primary coil of our step-up transformer.

87
00:14:14,750 --> 00:14:22,390
I made these contact terminals from copper wire.

88
00:14:23,390 --> 00:14:31,110
Now put them on a switch leg and

89
00:14:37,470 --> 00:14:40,230
restore it to its place.

90
00:15:07,200 --> 00:15:15,020
After this manipulation it'll be easy to combine this terminal with the opposite switch leg.

91
00:15:15,760 --> 00:15:22,880
Shift it, and we'll need to solder it later.

92
00:15:23,640 --> 00:15:31,060
Before final assembly we should check whether there's contact between the switch and the heat sink.

93
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:39,940
Switch the multimeter to diode-test mode and touch the middle leads of the transistors.

94
00:15:44,220 --> 00:15:50,820
You see the insulation is present — all in order.

95
00:15:52,020 --> 00:15:58,800
Since we have a low-voltage system, I don't check this module for high voltage.

96
00:15:58,940 --> 00:16:17,560
But if I'm building systems that'll work with rectified mains voltage, I additionally test instead of with a meter — for breakdown at 300 V DC through an incandescent lamp

97
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:19,280
the same way.

98
00:16:19,280 --> 00:16:29,760
This gives a reliable guarantee that the block won't need to be disassembled later — because that's quite labor-intensive.

99
00:16:30,860 --> 00:16:37,800
Now the switches are lightly tightened and rotate freely on their fastening points.

100
00:16:38,800 --> 00:16:51,000
This is done so you can conveniently place the plastic cover according to the fastening points.

101
00:16:53,160 --> 00:16:58,190
When fitting into the holes, the switches will shift slightly.

102
00:16:58,190 --> 00:17:10,390
If you fasten them in advance, this operation will be hard to do without additional bending of switch leads, which is undesirable.

103
00:17:12,190 --> 00:17:19,190
First fasten the regular fastenings.

104
00:17:21,770 --> 00:17:26,550
And now you see all the leads match.

105
00:17:26,550 --> 00:17:37,610
And these holes are needed so you can preliminarily tighten the switches from the top.

106
00:17:41,670 --> 00:17:43,830
Doing the tightening.

107
00:17:53,460 --> 00:18:00,280
Now we can release the regular fastenings.

108
00:18:04,690 --> 00:18:11,370
After this we move to soldering the middle leads.

109
00:18:12,370 --> 00:18:20,770
And subsequent tightening of the screw fastenings of the switches.

110
00:18:23,070 --> 00:18:32,410
You see the middle leads easily slip on in this position.

111
00:18:37,270 --> 00:18:41,170
This way we make the work easier for ourselves.

112
00:18:41,170 --> 00:18:50,450
For quality soldering of these joints I use organic electronics flux.

113
00:18:50,670 --> 00:18:57,410
It doesn't need washing and cleans contact surfaces very well.

114
00:18:57,750 --> 00:18:59,910
Also smells like pine forest.

115
00:19:00,690 --> 00:19:01,750
Very convenient.

116
00:19:04,230 --> 00:19:07,750
The soldering iron heats up to 380 degrees.

117
00:19:07,750 --> 00:19:09,610
Tip cleaned.

118
00:19:11,350 --> 00:19:16,270
After this take a drop of solder.

119
00:19:19,390 --> 00:19:23,070
Hold the contact pad.

120
00:19:24,530 --> 00:19:26,530
Solder.

121
00:19:36,320 --> 00:19:37,240
One half.

122
00:19:40,480 --> 00:19:43,020
A bit more flux.

123
00:20:05,350 --> 00:20:11,710
You need to fill the contact surface qualitatively.

124
00:20:31,490 --> 00:20:34,590
You can see how the solder spreads.

125
00:20:37,670 --> 00:20:43,050
Now remove this drop of flux.

126
00:20:45,770 --> 00:20:53,270
Plus, it doesn't conduct current, which is very good.

127
00:20:58,760 --> 00:21:05,440
And similarly solder the second contact pad.

128
00:21:06,180 --> 00:21:09,180
After soldering, you get this kind of beauty.

129
00:21:11,180 --> 00:21:22,480
There's one more important moment to pay attention to when buying power switches.

130
00:21:22,820 --> 00:21:30,540
It's preferable that they're from the same batch and the same manufacturer.

131
00:21:31,380 --> 00:21:35,590
Pay attention to letter and number symbols.

132
00:21:35,590 --> 00:21:40,070
These inscriptions on the switches should be identical.

133
00:21:41,990 --> 00:21:53,510
Now we can tighten the power switches while holding them with fingers to keep them from shifting.

134
00:21:54,470 --> 00:22:06,520
Tightening should be done with good force for quality heat removal.

135
00:22:09,500 --> 00:22:16,520
So the bolts you fasten them with should have a good wide head.

136
00:22:32,840 --> 00:22:37,260
Now we just need to bring power busses to our build.

137
00:22:37,780 --> 00:22:46,840
For critical devices I make them from quality copper cable with 2.5 mm² cross-section, in thermal insulation.

138
00:22:46,840 --> 00:22:52,740
The cable marking is RKDM, cost 70 rubles per meter.

139
00:22:53,300 --> 00:23:00,040
It has thermally stable insulation on its surface plus thermally stable braiding.

140
00:23:00,780 --> 00:23:12,540
I use it where I need to supply power in 220 V networks and where temperatures exceed 100 degrees.

141
00:23:14,320 --> 00:23:24,560
So that it can easily be threaded into the rings on the power switches, the ends of such cable should be tinned.

142
00:23:27,020 --> 00:23:28,600
Quality tinning.

143
00:23:28,760 --> 00:23:32,820
Now pass through the ring.

144
00:23:37,850 --> 00:23:53,970
After the wire is seated in the ring, you should crimp it with the power switch lead.

145
00:24:05,460 --> 00:24:08,460
This way we provide good contact.

146
00:24:08,460 --> 00:24:15,520
Now apply flux for soldering and,

147
00:24:25,180 --> 00:24:26,820
solder it.

148
00:24:31,380 --> 00:24:36,080
Heat it up well and feed solder.

149
00:25:15,300 --> 00:25:19,860
Same operation with the second wire.

150
00:25:22,520 --> 00:25:24,240
Pass it through,

151
00:25:28,410 --> 00:25:29,470
crimp.

152
00:26:39,620 --> 00:26:45,260
And with this, the power module can be considered finished.

153
00:26:47,320 --> 00:26:56,980
It only remains to connect the primary winding of the pulse transformer at these points.

154
00:26:59,940 --> 00:27:12,420
Next in our video series about the power supply will be winding the power transformer.

155
00:27:13,080 --> 00:27:18,160
Winding rules, taps, interlayer insulation.

156
00:27:19,360 --> 00:27:23,320
Will be interesting, but the work is painstaking.
